        <profileDesc>
            <creation>This story, with the short title "Mary Returns an Escaped Prisoner," is old: the earliest PEMM manuscript* in which this story appears is from around<date>1580</date>.Originally composed in <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC3010Ethiop">Ethiopia</placeName></creation>
            <abstract>
                <p>A wealthy governor’s official named Yoseph is tasked with ensuring a prisoner does not escape. While guarding the prisoner, Yoseph hosted a feast to honor Mary’s Dormition. Yoseph offered the man food. However, the prisoner refused to eat, since his shackles were too tight, and a log tied around his neck caused too much pain. Yoseph said he would untie the log if the prisoner promised Mary he would not escape, under punishment of her wrath. Despite making the oath, the prisoner escaped, causing Yoseph much fear and anger. After Yoseph prayed to Mary, the escaped prisoner was recaptured and imprisoned under harsher conditions.</p>
            </abstract>
